entry.et: Middle English helthe, from Old English hǣlth, from hāl

def.dt: :the condition of being sound in body, mind, or spirit
:the general condition of the body in poor health enjoys good health
:flourishing condition :well-being defending the health of the beloved oceans Peter Wilkinson
:general condition or state poor economic health
:a toast to someone's health or prosperity
:efforts made to maintain or restore health especially by trained and licensed professionals usually hyphenated when used attributively
:a usually commercial establishment having members who pay a fee to use its health and fitness facilities and equipment
:a food promoted as highly conducive to health
:insurance against loss through illness of the insured
:a certificate given to the ship's master at the time of leaving port that indicates the state of health of a ship's company and of a port with regard to infectious diseases
:a usually favorable report following an examination or investigation gave the criticized textbook a clean bill of health
:a day that an employee takes off from work in order to relieve stress or renew vitality
:the art and science dealing with the protection and improvement of community health by organized community effort and including preventive medicine and sanitary and social science
